You may have provided a link, but that doesn't make it true, Lurikeen.  I could provide lots of links and i am sure you would say they were not true.  You are basically stating that there is one writer who believes that these documents are false, and by stating they are false, it makes them so.  There are many other historians and scholars who do not consider these sources to be false.  I'm not the scholar.  You're not the scholar.  We didn't carbon date anything, but we read about it.  In the end, it doesn't really matter, it still comes down to the fact that you choose to believe that person's assessment and I do not.  You have based your opinions on sources, as have I.  As for answering the papers points point by point, I probably could find someone who does exactly that kind of thing and have them do it.  My point, is why?  If you think you might change your mind, then I'll do it.  If you are only making that statement to be difficult or to mock, then its not worth my time.<br>
<br>
2) You are correct in my mentioning that the scrolls do not contain the Christian canon in its entirety.  It contains the Hebrew Bible.  Which is part of the Christian Bible.  <br>
<br>
3) <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Indeed, that would be impossible given that the Christian Scriptures where not canonized until the 4th Century CE.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
First,I am not sure what this has to do with the actual birth, death and rez of Jesus?  I mentioned the Dead Sea Scrolls as proof of the validity of the Bible (or parts thereof), carbon dated actually from 250 bc to 90 ad (some say 6<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> .  The earliest manuscript of Mark is actually dated to withing 20 years of Christ's death.  If you mention the canonization fo the Bible as evidence that Christ did not exist, well here is an answer for you which includes Old and New testament.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Canon<br>
This word is derived from a Hebrew and Greek word denoting a reed or cane. Hence it means something straight, or something to keep straight; and hence also a rule, or something ruled or measured. It came to be applied to the Scriptures, to denote that they contained the authoritative rule of faith and practice, the standard of doctrine and duty. A book is said to be of canonical authority when it has a right to take a place with the other books which contain a revelation of the Divine will. Such a right does not arise from any ecclesiastical authority, but from the evidence of the inspired authorship of the book. The canonical (i.e., the inspired) books of the Old and New Testaments, are a complete rule, and the only rule, of faith and practice. They contain the whole supernatural revelation of God to men. The New Testament Canon was formed gradually under divine guidance. The different books as they were written came into the possession of the Christian associations which began to be formed soon after the day of Pentecost; and thus slowly the canon increased till all the books were gathered together into one collection containing the whole of the twenty-seven New Testament inspired books. Historical evidence shows that from about the middle of the second century this New Testament collection was substantially such as we now possess. Each book contained in it is proved to have, on its own ground, a right to its place; and thus the whole is of divine authority.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
(Do me a favor and don't argue the point above that these books were not divinely inspired. we already know you dont believe it.)<br>
<br>
4) <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Further, there are no explicit references to Jesus in the Dead Sea Scrolls. If you think Jesus is explicitly mentioned then please cite the reference.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The Messiah is explicity mentioned many times.  jesus us not mentioned by name, only the Messiah.  I can, however, give some arguments for you of examples.  Here are two arguments 1) the scrolls contain Isaiah in its entirety, all books.  There are predicitons of the messiah in these books regarding who he would be, what he would do, when he would arrive, how he would die, and when for all of these things, specifically Is. 53 to name one.  There are over 700 specific predicitons regarding the coming of the Messiah in the Old Testament, and its amazing that Jesus fullfilled them all (of course in my view, you might argue that point, I understand this).  2)  The other mention is actually a non-biblical manuscript called 4Q521.  There is an added phrase that mentions wonders the Messiah would do when he came, namely &quot;the dead will walk.&quot;  It is later in Christ's life and recorded in Matt. 11:4-5 , that Christ answers when questioned regarding who he was &quot;Go back and report to John what you hear and see:........the dead are raised, and the good news is preached to the poor.&quot;  (Omission of some lines mine cause I didnt want to type them, see Matt. 11:4-5 for full text).  Clearly, Jesus was asserting himself as that he was the Messiah, fullfilling the Messianic prophecy mentioned in the scrolls. I find it amazing that Jesus said this and that we later find it recorded in a book of Is. that predates jesus.  it isnt as if jesus read this and said to himself, &quot;let me make sure to say that so that I am fulfilling a prophecy so I can scam the people of the world into thinking I am the Messiah.&quot;<br>
<br>
Thats as good as the mentions of Jesus are in the Dead Sea Scrolls, Lurikeen.  However, let me point out again, that when I was mentioning the Dea Sea Scrolls, it was in reply to your claims (well sorry not yours that writers which you believe) that not only did Jesus never live, but that the entire Christian religion was made up by a few men.<br>
<br>
I have one quote for that which I find awesome.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> The popular historian Will Durant, himself not a Christian, wrote concerning Christ's historical validity, &quot;The denial of that existence seems never to have occurred even to the bitterest gentile or Jewish opponents of nascent Christianity&quot; (Durant, The Story of Civilization, vol. 3, p. 555). And again, &quot;That a few simple men should in one generation have invented so powerful and appealing a personality, so lofty an ethic and so inspiring a vision of human brotherhood, would be a miracle far more incredible than any recorded in the Gospels&quot; (Ibid., p. 557). <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
5) You bring up other religions and their validity.  Of course I don't believe that these other religions are 100% true. I certainly do not believe that Mohammed performed any miracles.  And no, I don't believe that the book of Mormon is correct.  If someone could give me as much hard evidence as I have for Jesus, I would look at these other religions again.  I helped a friend investigate these other religions, nothing else made sense to me Lurikeen.  However, that is not so for everyone. Just because I believe in one God who became flesh does not mean that I don't think that people have a right to believe what they want or that I am intolerant.  I simply do not choose to believe what they do.  I am sure that people of other religions would find me misguided and would not have any problem telling me so.  I would not believe they were being malcious or mean or arrogant, I simply would think they were misguided. What I think the problem really is here is that you do not want me to open my mouth.  Its fine if I believe what I want as long as I keep my mouth shut and don't share it. Well, sorry Lurikeen, but thats silly.  You share your views and I find them valid and well thought out.  I am simply doing the same.  I think you boggle my mind because I feel you are refusing to investigate, and I bet I boggle your mind because you just cannot believe what I do.<br>
<br>
I will finish here with a quote to you:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> The kind of evidence used in historical research is the same kind as that used in a court of law. In a courtroom case certain kinds of evidences are appealed to in order to determine what exactly happened, eyewitnesses are questioned, motives are examined, and physical evidence is scrutinized such as fingerprints or journal writings. <br>
<br>
It is the same kind of evidence that we appeal to in order to establish Christ's life, death, and resurrection. Granted, the evidence is not as great as that for Lincoln, nor as recent. But it is better evidence than we have that Plato ever lived, or Homer, or many historical figures that we take for granted.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
For me, the evidence was enough to convince me when I had doubts, and yes of course, I have had them.  I am not intolerant of other religions, but this thread was specifically devoted to the belief in the existence of God.  I am not the one who started the debate, but sure I love discussing these things with people, not because it gives me a chance to go preach (I am not good at that) but because I get to have a stimulating conversation with other people.<br>
<br>
I must in the end, thank you.  you have made me look up answers to questions and investigate my faith in order to attempt to debate with you, and it has truly deepened my belief and my faith and my conviction.  I know you don't believe as I do, thats ok Lurikeen.  I still wish you well, I still think you are a worthy human being.  I still hope you find fulfillment in this life.<br>
<br>
I've said I'm done a hundred times, but this time I really am.  i truly only came back because I discovered I had ommitted a major point when speaking on this issue and I needed to correct that.  Like I said, I'm not a scholar, I enver pretended to be.  i think that there are plenty of books out there who could debate these issues better than I with you Lurikeen, if you really truly want to know more or debate more, then let me know through email, and i will pass your information along to someone who is more gifted in thsi area than I.<br>
<br>
Best Wishes to you in life,<br>
<br>
Luk<br>
