Nope. That is not true Lukaria. The dead sea scrolls contain fragments of specific books found in the Christian Old Testament. The Hebrew canon was not agreed upon until the Second Century CE so could not possibly contain the &quot;Hebrew Bible&quot; as you say. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> &quot;First,I am not sure what this has to do with the actual birth, death and rez of Jesus? I mentioned the Dead Sea Scrolls as proof of the validity of the Bible (or parts thereof), carbon dated actually from 250 bc to 90 ad (some say 6 . The earliest manuscript of Mark is actually dated to withing 20 years of Christ's death. If you mention the canonization fo the Bible as evidence that Christ did not exist, well here is an answer for you which includes Old and New testament.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It has a lot to do with it. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  First, the early Christian church could not agree with what texts should be considered &quot;authoratative&quot;. Many different texts and oral traditions were floating about. Some of which claimed Jesus never died on the cross, that he was not crucified, that he had married and has children, etc. To this day, Lukaria, scholars are still skeptical as to whether or not the book of Revelation should be kept in the canon! The point is that the literature you turn to and use as &quot;evidence&quot; is really shaky at best. It is not contemporary to Jesus, the authors are unknown, the originals of the texts are lost forever, and what fragments and manuscripts are available have been grossly tampered with by scribes through out the ages. I read the quote you provided, too. Who are you quoting? Looks like a piece by Josh McDowell. At any rate, I can quote other Christian scholars who would flagrantly disagree with the source you provided.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> &quot;The Messiah is explicity mentioned many times. jesus us not mentioned by name, only the Messiah. I can, however, give some arguments for you of examples.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I am not even going to get into the so-called proof you offer based on the fullfillment of prophecies. Christians can't even agree on the nature of the prophetic content found in the Christian bible. I want to point out that there are several &quot;Messiahs&quot; mentioned by both the Hebrews and Romans around the time Jesus purportedly lived. A precursory understanding of biblical history would show you that the Hebrew traditions found in their apocalyptic writings always contain references to Messiahs generically as individuals who save them from their enemies. Interpretation of biblical references is a daunting task which has lead to the formation of hundreds of schisms in the Christian church throughout history. I would not pretend that there is a monolithic Christian view or interpretation of the Bible. At any rate, Jesus is not explicitly mentioned in the Dead Sea scrolls and Messianic references contained there in will not be helpful either, since the question will always be &quot;Which Messiah is being referred to?&quot;<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> &quot;You bring up other religions and their validity. Of course I don't believe that these other religions are 100% true. I certainly do not believe that Mohammed performed any miracles. And no, I don't believe that the book of Mormon is correct. If someone could give me as much hard evidence as I have for Jesus, I would look at these other religions again. I helped a friend investigate these other religions, nothing else made sense to me Lurikeen. However, that is not so for everyone.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
